   <mods:abstract>Containers such as Docker and Singularity encapsulate complex programs with their dependencies in isolated environments and offer fast, customizable, portable, and flexible deployments of applications. The containerization technology eases the deployment of High-Performance Computing (HPC) instances in the cloud computing environment, facilitating the migration of HPC applications to the cloud. Another important aspect for HPC applications to run in cloud environments is security. Encrypted communication is essential for HPC applications that process sensitive data. Encryption and decryption operations are expensive operations. Hence, new algorithms and protocols need to be developed to efficiently support security. Additionally, cloud computing platforms employ virtualization technology, and achieving efficient secure communication on virtualized environments presents added complexity. In this dissertation research, we have developed and evaluated techniques to support secure communication, in an efficient way, over virtualized environments using container technology. This exploration occurred in multiple steps. Initially, we developed novel algorithms for the collective operations within the Message Passing Interface (MPI) library, with a specific focus on the all-reduce operation. Additionally, we contributed to the development of a secure MPI library called CryptMPI. We participated in integrating and standardizing the developed encrypted operations within CryptMPI. In the second step, we examined CryptMPI's behavior across container clusters. We evaluated CryptMPI's performance on various container engines, such as Docker and Singularity, to gauge its effectiveness within the virtualized clusters. Moreover, we conducted a comprehensive comparison of the different built-in encryption mechanisms offered by container managers, specifically focusing on Docker Swarm and Kubernetes, and compared the gathered results with those of CryptMPI. In the final step, we explored other encryption schemes for CryptMPI, offering better performance for small message sizes. In this survey, we combined all of these state-of-the-art techniques to develop a novel and well-designed secure MPI library.</mods:abstract>
